    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-13T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-13T12:00:00-05:00" n="218"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d218">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">850.33/5–1354: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 218<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Representative to the European Coal and
                        Steel Community (<persName corresp="#p_BRUCEDKE1" type="from"
                            >Bruce</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d218fn1">Repeated to London, Bonn, Rome, The Hague,
                        Brussels, and Luxembourg.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">limited official use</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-13T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 13, 1954—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Coled1">Coled</gloss> 240. Subject: European Coal and Steel
                    Community.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Annual meeting of Common Assembly<note n="2" xml:id="d218fn2">The Second
                            Ordinary Session of the Common Assembly of the European Coal and Steel
                            Community met in Strasbourg, May 11–19. This series of meetings was
                            followed by the first part of the Sixth Ordinary Session of the
                            Consultative Assembly of the Council of Europe, which met in Strasbourg
                            May 20–29; both assemblies held a joint meeting on May 20–21. For a
                            record of the meetings of the Consultative Assembly, see <hi
                                rend="italic">Minutes of Proceedings</hi> (Strasbourg, 1954) and
                            Official Report of Debates (Strasbourg, 1954). A summary of the joint
                            meeting of the Common Assembly and Consultative Assembly was transmitted
                            to the Department of State in despatch 237 from Strasbourg, May 21.
                            (740.00/5–2154)</note> opened Tuesday and unanimously elected <persName
                            corresp="#p_DEGASPERIA1">De Gasperi</persName> as President to succeed
                            <persName corresp="#p_SPAAKPH1">Spaak</persName>. <pb facs="0441"
                            n="393" xml:id="pg_393"/> Italian observers believe <persName
                            corresp="#p_DEGASPERIA1">De Gasperi</persName>’s election will greatly
                        enhance his prestige in Italy and might make it possible for him to speed up
                        drive for <gloss target="#t_EDC1">EDC</gloss> ratification in Italy.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MONNETJ1">Monnet</persName> reported yesterday on
                        developments of last year. He emphasized Common Market has become reality
                        without leading to catastrophic economic effects foretold by some critics.
                        He promised energetic action against existing cartel organizations and
                        excessive concentrations including possibly Charbonnages de France. He
                        assured several times that labor interests being protected and outlined
                        measures to this effect including allocation 25 million dollars for workers’
                        housing out of US loan. He described American loan as manifestation of
                        political and economic credit of community. No further details given as to
                        lending policy of High Authority. Discussion on report begins today.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Have returned this morning to Paris in view Saar discussions between
                        French and Germans scheduled for today.<note n="3" xml:id="d218fn3">For
                            documentation concerning Saar negotiations, see <ref
                                target="frus1952-54v05p2#pg_1370">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">v</hi>,
                                Part 2, pp. 1370</ref> ff.</note> Plan to be in Strasbourg for
                        Council of Ministers meeting next Tuesday.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BRUCEDKE1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bruce</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
